\section{Results}
\lipsum[9-10] % Generates random text

\section{Discussion}
\lipsum[11-12] % Generates random text

\end{document}
```
In this example, the `\tableofcontents` command is used to generate the table of contents. The `\section` and `\subsection` commands are used to create sections and subsections in the document, which will automatically be included in the table of contents. The `\lipsum` command is used to generate random text for the example.

When you compile this document, LaTeX will automatically generate a table of contents based on the sections and subsections you have defined. The table of contents will be formatted according to the document class and any other formatting options you have specified.

To draw a chessboard with a specific FEN (Forsyth-Edwards Notation) in LaTeX, you can use the `tikz` package. Here is a step-by-step guide to create a LaTeX code for drawing a chessboard with a FEN:

1. First, include the necessary packages by adding the following lines to the preamble of your LaTeX document:

```latex
\usepackage{xparse}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{chains,positioning}
```

2. Create a new command to parse the FEN string and draw the chessboard:

```latex
\NewDocumentCommand{\drawBoard}{m}{%
  % Set up the chessboard
  \begin{tikzpicture}[
    start chain=going below,
    node distance=0pt,
    every node/.style={
      on chain,
      inner sep=0pt,
      outer sep=0pt,
      minimum size=1cm,
      text width=1cm,
      align=center,
      font=\sffamily
    },
    white/.style={fill=white},
    black/.style={fill=gray!30},
    empty/.style={draw=none,fill=none},
    piece/.style={text=white}
  ]

  % Loop through the FEN string
  \foreach \x [count=\y] in {#1} {
    % If the character is a digit, create that many empty squares
    \IfInteger{\x}{
      \foreach \z in {1,...,\x} {
        \node[empty];
      }
    }
    % If the character is a lowercase letter, create a black square and place the corresponding piece
    \elseif{\x<=z}{
      \node[black];
      \node[piece,above=0pt] {\textsc{\x}};
    }
    % If the character is an uppercase letter, create a white square and place the corresponding piece
    \elseif{\x>z}{
      \node[white];
      \node[piece,above=0pt] {\textsc{\lowercase\x}};
    }
    % If the character is a forward slash, start a new row
    \elseif{\x==0}{
      \node[empty];
      \tikzset{start chain=going right,node distance=1cm}
      \begin{scope}[start chain=going below]
      \node[on chain,white];
      \end{scope}
    }
  }

  % Reset the chain direction for the next board
  \tikzset{start chain=going below}
  \end{tikzpicture}%
}
```

3. Now, you can use the `\drawBoard` command to draw a chessboard with a specific FEN. For example, to draw a chessboard with the starting position FEN `rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR`, add the following line to your LaTeX document:

```latex
\drawBoard{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR}
```

