```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        double log = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return Math.abs(log - Math.floor(log)) < 0.000001;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(1)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(9)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(81)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(243)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(45)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(10)); // false
    }
}
```

This solution uses the `Math.log` function to calculate the logarithm base 3 of the input number `n`. If `n` is a power of three, the result should be an integer. The code checks if the difference between the logarithm value and its floor value is close enough to 0 (within a small tolerance of 0.000001) to determine if it's a power of three or not.

However, this solution has a limitation: it may not work correctly for very large input numbers due to the finite precision of floating-point numbers. In such cases, you can use a bitwise solution, like the one below:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThreeBitwise(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(27)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(0)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(-1)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(1)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(9)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(81)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(243)); // true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(45)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(10)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(Integer.MAX_VALUE)); // false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThreeBitwise(1162261467)); // true
    }
}
```

This bitwise solution repeatedly divides the input number `n` by 3 and checks the remainder until the quotient is no longer divisible by 3. If the final quotient is 1, then `n` is a power of three. This solution has no issues with large input numbers.

